    "pbj_collapsible_content_8FaULY": {
      "type": "pbj-collapsible-content",
      "blocks": {
        "collapsible_row_nQDxCJ": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Is there alcohol in BERO?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Technically, yes, but just a touch below 0.5% ABV, which is considered to be the legal threshold for non-alcoholic beverages. For comparison, soy sauce is made through a natural brewing process similar to beer and typically contains 1.5-2% ABV, and no one’s calling that a cocktail.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_WVGMng": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Can I drink BERO if breastfeeding or pregnant?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Always consult your physician before consumption. That’s important in any health-related decision. While it’s unlikely that non-alcoholic beverages—in moderation—would pose a risk, there is no safe level of alcohol intake when pregnant or breastfeeding.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_ncqNhA": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How many calories are in each beer?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<ul><li>Kingston Golden Pils: 88 calories</li><li>Edge Hill Hazy IPA: 73 calories</li><li>Noon Wheat: 70 calories</li><li>Double Tasty West Coast Style IPA: 90 calories</li></ul>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_KL49AR": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How many carbs are in each beer?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<ul><li>Kingston Golden Pils: 19 g per 12 fl. oz </li><li>Edge Hill Hazy IPA: 15 g per 12 fl. oz </li><li>Noon Wheat: 15 g per 12 fl. oz</li><li>Double Tasty West Coast Style IPA: 18 g per 12 fl. oz </li></ul>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_TA9YKc": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How is BERO made?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>For the beer aficionados out there, we start with the same foundational steps as a full-strength beer by creating a “mash” with our high-quality malts. From this mash, our solution of sugars, called wort, is obtained. By brewing at higher temperatures, we obtain a blend that’s intentionally lighter on alcohol but big on flavor. We start our wort at 5-6%—versus the usual heavy-hitting 12-13% for a regular beer. Next, we introduce a special maltose-negative yeast. Fancy name, but here’s what matters: this yeast doesn't consume the malt sugar (maltose), but it works its magic on simpler sugars like glucose. To put it simply, we brew in a way where we don’t need to remove the alcohol because we aren’t creating any alcohol to remove. Our beer then goes through a natural fermentation process. No tricks, no shortcuts. What really makes BERO stand out is our malts—giving every sip a rich, full-bodied taste with unmistakable character that sets our brews apart.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_9Q6zG6": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What ingredients are in BERO’s beer?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<ul><li>Kingston Golden Pils: Water, malted barley, hops, yeast</li><li>Edge Hill Hazy IPA: Water, malted barley, malted wheat, malted oats, hops, yeast</li><li>Noon Wheat: Water, malted barley, malted wheat, malted oats, hops, yeast, and other natural flavors</li><li>Double Tasty West Coast Style IPA: Water, malt, hops, yeast, and other natural hop flavors</li></ul>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": "ingredients-faq"
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_7KGqDG": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "I am diabetic, can I drink BERO?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Always consult your physician before consumption. That’s important in any health-related decision. The product does have carbohydrate content.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_4WBLCJ": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What allergens are contained in BERO products?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Wheat.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_98j7Rf": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Does BERO contain yeast, wheat, gluten, or dairy?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Yes, our beers contain yeast, gluten (because of the malts), and wheat. This is part of the natural brewing process. However, our beer is dairy-free.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_fABMeW": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Does BERO contain any added sugar?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>None. We believe in letting the natural flavors shine.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_yAeyxA": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Is BERO certified Kosher?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Not at the moment. Keep an eye out for updates on our website. </p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_qNhweE": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Is BERO vegan?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>BERO is not currently “vegan certified”, but it could be considered vegan. We do not use any animal-derived ingredients in our recipes, including honey, nor do we use any animal-based finings or filter aids  in our beers.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_FyLMqV": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Do you have a regenerative agriculture certification?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Not at the moment; however, we are considering it. Keep an eye out for updates on our website.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_Y9izGM": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What is the expiration date of a BERO?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Your BERO’s “best by” date can be found on the bottom of every can and on the carton. In some cases, you may see a batch number instead of a “best by” date, in which case the expiration date is 365 days from that date.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_9ECmBL": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "How should I store my beer?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>Whenever possible, store your beer cold / cool—below 50 degrees Fahrenheit is the sweet spot. Never expose your beer to hot temperatures or heat sources.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        },
        "collapsible_row_JmHMgL": {
          "type": "collapsible_row",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "What is the optimal drinking temperature?",
            "open_collapsible": false,
            "icon": "none",
            "row_content": "<p>BERO is best enjoyed between 36–40 degrees Fahrenheit.</p>",
            "page": "",
            "anchor": ""
          }
        }
      },
